answers.answer: I wouldn't worry about that. It's barely out of the normal range, and phosphorus isn't something that physicians get worried about usually.
Yeah thanks, I actually spoke with my doctor and he said that it was because I recently ate a lot of seafood (which it's true). Sooo, problem solved. ;)

HiWelcome to the MedHelp forum!High phosphorus is usually due to high phosphorus intake, hypoparathyroidsm, uncontrolled diabetes, and kidney failure. High phosphorus is found in cheese, meat, egg, lentils, nuts, milk etc. The reading is marginally higher. Repeat the test and see.  Also consult your PCP regarding the diseases causing high phosphorus. Take care!
